where the public interest demands that the court should not merely give its imprimatur to the private agreement of the parties — either because of the nature of the proceedings (eg, probate proceedings, see 
[SCR Pt 78.37.1]
) or because the point in contention involves a matter of general public interest or significance and a consent order might wrongly be interpreted as a definitive determination: Myer Queenstown Garden Plaza Pty Ltd v Port Adelaide City Council (1975) 33 LGRA 70 at 82 ; BMI Ltd v Federated Clerks' Union of Australia (1983) 51 ALR 401; 76 FLR 141 ;
